      <div type="translation">
        <p>On the 7th day of the … in year 20 … Māṭharīputta Siri-Vīrapurisadatta, (son) of the Great King Siri-Cāntamūla — sacrificer of the Aśvamedha, giver of numerous tens of millions of [pieces of] gold, (hundreds of thousands of cows and hundreds of thousands of plows of land) —, who increased …, whose commands were received on the head by [kings of?] Tosala, Kosala, Paṭu, and Magadha, the overlord of the Viñjha (Vindhya) mountain ... and Siripavvata (Śrīparvata), who has obtained majesty ... in many battles — this image has been established.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary">
        <p n="3">
          <note>Our translation is based on the assumption that the word <foreign xml:lang="pra-Brah">putasa</foreign> has been lost in the lacuna at the end of this line.</note>
        </p>
        <p n="4">
          <term>k<unclear>a</unclear>mal<gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"></gap></term>
          <note>This first epithet is at present obscure to us.<!--Perhaps vāsaka is the end of °uvāsaka (AG)?--></note>
        </p>
        <p n="4–5">
          <term><supplied reason="lost">to</supplied>salakosalapaṭuma<unclear>gha</unclear>dhi-</term>
          <note>This compound is composed of four place-names, the first two of which form a pair commonly encountered in the literature, and discussed at length in <bibl><ptr target="bib:Lévi1923"></ptr>: <citedRange>1–11</citedRange></bibl>. The third toponym, <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">paṭu</foreign>, is more obscure, but the <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">paṭavas</foreign> or people of Paṭu feature in Purāṇic lists of people living in the Vindhyas (cf. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Sircar1971"></ptr>: <citedRange>44</citedRange></bibl>). Their exact location is uncertain. Finally, <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">maghadhi</foreign> seems to point to the inhabitants of Magadha, where the aspiration of the final consonant seems to have been imposed also on the second one. The form <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">maghada</foreign> with full inversion of aspiration is encountered in the manuscript tradition of the Śaktisaṅgamatantra, as noted in <bibl><ptr target="bib:Sircar1971"></ptr>: <citedRange>85</citedRange></bibl>.</note>
          <!--The form maghadha occurs also twice in Tripathi’s edition of the Br̥hatsaṃhitā 11:55 and 32:11. I don’t have the edition at hand and that of Bhatt has the regular magadha (VT)-->
        </p>
        <p n="5–6">
          <term>-sira<unclear>sā</unclear><supplied reason="lost">saṁpaṭi</supplied>chitasāsanasa</term>
          <note>Our reconstruction here is informed by the occurrence of the phrase <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">sirasā saṁpaṭicchitasāsana</foreign>, meaning “whose rule/teaching has been accepted by [the bowing of] the head” in Pali commentarial literature. See Dīghanikāyaṭṭhakathāṭikā (ed. De Silva 1970) III 158.4–5: <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">gahetabbavacano sirasā sampaṭicchitasāsano</foreign>; Paramatthadīpanī (ed. Bose 1934–36) I 78.8–10: <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">evaṁmahānubhāvo ti cakkaratanādisamannāgamena kassaci pi pīḷaṁ akaronto va sabbarājūhi sirasā sampaṭicchitasāsanavehāsagamanādīhi evaṁ mahānubhāvo</foreign>.<!--Alternatively, one could also imagine a reconstruction *<foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">anatichitasāsana</foreign> (≈ <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">anatītaśāsana</foreign>)—cf. Vogel’s (1929-30) explanation of <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">atichita</foreign>- in the Nagarjunakonda inscriptions—but we consider this option less convincing, and anyhow it is unsupported by external evidence.--></note>
        </p>
        <p n="7–8">
          <term>ba<unclear>hu</unclear>sa<unclear>mara</unclear><gap quantity="2" reason="lost" unit="character"></gap><unclear>la</unclear>dhapatāpasa</term>
          <note>However we reconstruct this compound, it is clear that it offers an interesting antecedent to royal epithets bore by Viṣṇukuṇḍin rulers and Pr̥thivīśrīmūla. See, for instance, EIAD <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00181.xml">181</ref>, l. 5: <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">cānekacāturddantasamaraśatasahasrasaṅghaṭṭavijayī</foreign>; <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00186.xml">186</ref>, st. II: <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">bahusamarajayopāttonatataśrīr</foreign>; <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00189.xml">189</ref>, ll. 7–9: <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">°asakr̥danekaniśitanistriṁśasahasrasaṁkulātibhīmasaṁgrāmabhūmipratilabdhavijayī</foreign>. This feat of king Vīrapurisadatta is also likely hinted at in one of the two narrative reliefs preserved on the pillar itself, which shows the ruler riding an elephant and accompanied by soldiers.</note>
        </p>
